<!--
  TrueNAS SCALE syslog -> Wazuh decoders.
  Source: a TrueNAS SCALE host sending RFC5424 syslog over TCP/514 to the Wazuh manager
          (a <remote><connection>syslog</connection> block in the manager config).

  >> SUBSTITUTE FOR YOUR ENVIRONMENT: these decoders anchor on the TrueNAS syslog HOSTNAME token,
     shown throughout as 'true' (an example short hostname). Replace 'true' in every prematch below
     with your TrueNAS host's syslog hostname (e.g. 'truenas'), and set your own <TRUENAS IP> /
     <LAN CIDR> in the manager's syslog <remote> allowed-ips.

  WIRE/DELIVERY FORM (ground-truthed from logall_json archives):
    wazuh-remoted does NOT de-frame RFC6587 octet-counting and does NOT strip <PRI>, so the
    string analysisd actually sees is:
        <OCTET-COUNT> <PRI>1 <ISO8601-ts> true <APP> <PROCID> <MSGID> <STRUCTURED-DATA> <MSG>
        e.g.  693 <10>1 2026-06-04T11:14:45-04:00 true TNAUDIT_SYSTEM - - [meta sequenceId="9"] @cee:{...}
              128 <86>1 2026-06-04T11:14:26-04:00 true ed 1284 - - pam_unix(truenas-unix:session): session opened ...
              192 <38>1 2026-06-04T11:39:26-04:00 true sshd-session 961768 - - Accepted publickey for X from Y port N
    The default pre-decoder can't parse the ISO8601 stamp, so hostname/program_name come back
    EMPTY and no stock decoder matches. These decoders re-parse the raw line.

  HARD-WON os_regex / Wazuh gotchas verified on 4.14.5 (all cost a reload to discover):
    1. pcre2 <prematch> on a first-level decoder (no <program_name>) does NOT reliably match.
       Use native os_regex (like the stock web-accesslog decoder, which DOES match these lines).
    2. os_regex chokes on a literal '<PRI>' sub-pattern ('<\d+>'); match each leading token with
       \S+ instead (\S matches the '<86>1' bytes fine; only the literal angle-bracket pattern fails).
    3. The prematch + regex must be '^'-anchored for field extraction to fire.
    4. A decoder that is a PARENT (has child decoders) does NOT run its own <regex>/<order> — it is
       only a prematch gate. So 'truenas' (which extracts truenas_app via its own <regex>/<order>)
       must stay CHILDLESS. New SSH extractors are therefore SEPARATE first-level decoders ordered
       BEFORE 'truenas' (more specific prematch wins), NOT children of 'truenas'.
    5. Among first-level decoders the FIRST whose prematch matches wins (and stops). Order is:
       'truenas-tnaudit' (@cee JSON) -> 'truenas-sshd-*' (specific sshd-session lines) -> 'truenas'
       (generic app-name fallback, last).
    6. JSON_Decoder does NOT recurse into double-encoded JSON strings. TrueNAS stores
       TNAUDIT.event_data and TNAUDIT.svc_data as serialized JSON *strings*, so dotted paths like
       TNAUDIT.event_data.method DO NOT EXIST. Rules must regex-match the whole TNAUDIT.event_data
       string value. Only genuinely-nested objects (TNAUDIT.vers, sudo.reject, sudo.accept) decode
       into dotted fields.

  CANONICAL FIELDS: the 'truenas-sshd-*' decoders map the real remote SSH
  address/user into Wazuh's canonical srcip / srcuser. MISP IP-IOC rules (100210/100211) auto-flag known-bad
  addresses, and same_source_ip frequency rules work for brute-force detection.

  WHY NO srcip ON TNAUDIT: we deliberately do NOT map TNAUDIT.addr -> srcip. Two hard reasons:
    (a) Empirically (1194 audit events) TNAUDIT.addr is 127.0.0.1 for all but one — it is the
        middleware's loopback self-view, not a useful client IP, so MISP correlation on it is moot.
    (b) Wazuh will not let you add canonical fields to a JSON-plugin decoder anyway: a child decoder
        SUPPRESSES the parent's plugin_decoder (verified on 4.14.5 — TNAUDIT.* vanish), and combining
        <regex>/<order> with <plugin_decoder> in one decoder is a hard config error (2111).
    The real external attack surface (SSH brute force from routable IPs) is captured with proper
    srcip by the sshd decoders below, so MISP/geo/frequency correlation works where it matters.
    TNAUDIT rules key on TNAUDIT.addr / TNAUDIT.user directly (as the existing 100345-100359 do).

  TNAUDIT_SYSTEM / TNAUDIT_MIDDLEWARE are the high-value sub-source (TrueNAS middleware audit).
  JSON_Decoder parses from immediately after the '@cee:' prematch -> TNAUDIT.* fields:
  event, success, user, addr, svc, svc_data(str), event_data(str), vers.* ; and for sudo lines
  -> sudo.reject.* / sudo.accept.* .
-->

<!-- (1) TNAUDIT middleware audit + sudo @cee:{json}.  Listed FIRST so it wins over 'truenas' for
        these lines.  prematch '@cee:' positions JSON_Decoder exactly at the '{'.  Handles BOTH
        @cee:{"TNAUDIT":...} and @cee:{"sudo":...} (sudo reject/accept). -->
<decoder name="truenas-tnaudit">
  <prematch>@cee:</prematch>
  <plugin_decoder offset="after_prematch">JSON_Decoder</plugin_decoder>
</decoder>

<!-- (2) TrueNAS SSH (program 'sshd-session').  Separate first-level decoders, ordered BEFORE
        'truenas' so the specific prematch wins; each extracts canonical srcuser/srcip.
        program_name is NOT usable here (empty due to the ISO8601 pre-decoder miss, gotcha #2),
        so we anchor on the raw octet/PRI/ts/host/app token sequence like 'truenas' does.
        Rules key on these via <decoded_as>. -->

<!-- (2a) Accepted login:  "... true sshd-session <pid> - - Accepted <method> for <user> from <ip> port .." -->
<decoder name="truenas-sshd-accept">
  <prematch>^\d+ \S+ \d\d\d\d-\d\d-\d\dT\S+ true sshd-session \S+ \S+ \S+ Accepted </prematch>
  <regex offset="after_prematch">^\S+ for (\S+) from (\S+) port</regex>
  <order>srcuser,srcip</order>
</decoder>

<!-- (2b) Failed login:  "... Failed <method> for [invalid user ]<user> from <ip> port .."
         Every failed SSH attempt (valid or invalid user) emits a "Failed password" line, so this
         one decoder is sufficient for brute-force detection. The optional "invalid user " infix is
         skipped so srcuser captures the actual attempted username in both shapes. -->
<decoder name="truenas-sshd-fail">
  <prematch type="pcre2">^\d+ \S+ \d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}T\S+ true sshd-session \S+ \S+ \S+ Failed </prematch>
  <regex offset="after_prematch" type="pcre2">^\S+ for (?:invalid user )?(\S+) from (\S+) port</regex>
  <order>srcuser,srcip</order>
</decoder>

<!-- (3) Any other TrueNAS RFC5424 line (general syslog: smartd, zed, systemd, kernel, ...): extract
        the app-name into truenas_app. Childless, so its <regex> runs. Ordered LAST so the specific
        @cee/sshd decoders win first. Unchanged from the original working decoder. -->
<decoder name="truenas">
  <prematch>^\d+ \S+ \d\d\d\d-\d\d-\d\dT\S+ true </prematch>
  <regex offset="after_prematch">^(\S+)</regex>
  <order>truenas_app</order>
</decoder>
